pipeline_messages.content:
You are an expert writing quality judge. You will evaluate three drafts
against a set of personalized rubric criteria. You also have access to the user's
recent conversation history for additional context about their preferences.

The three drafts are:
- Draft A = the **rubric-guided** draft (written following the user's rubric criteria)
- Draft B = the **generic** draft (written with no rubric — just competent writing)
- Draft C = the **original preference** draft (written from the user's stated preferences, before the rubric was created)

DRAFT A (rubric-guided):
I hadn't slept well — three nights into the trip and still running on a kind of jittery alertness that passes for energy until it doesn't. I found the stall by following a woman carrying a thermos, which felt like solid enough logic at 6am.

The cook was maybe sixty, working two pots simultaneously with the calm of someone who has made the same thing so many times that her hands have stopped consulting her brain. The stall was the size of a walk-in closet. I sat on a plastic stool that rocked slightly on the uneven concrete, and stayed anyway.

The khao tom came in a clay-colored bowl, the broth thinner than I expected — not creamy, more like water that had been convinced it was something else. Steam fogged my glasses when I leaned in. The rice had softened past individual grains into something closer to a slow dissolution, and there was ginger in it, cut thick enough that you'd hit a piece and get that brief sharp clearing behind the nose, the kind that makes you blink.

Around me: the wet slap of ladles, a radio playing something with a lot of treble, two older men at the next table eating in total silence with the ease of people who have been friends for forty years.

I didn't leave until my second bowl went cold. I don't entirely know why. Something about the indifference of the place — how nobody needed me to be having a meaningful moment — made it easier to just sit there and be a person eating breakfast.

DRAFT B (generic):
The market was still half-asleep when I found her stall, a single bulb swaying above a pot of rice porridge that had clearly been simmering since before dawn. I pointed, she nodded, and within minutes a bowl of khao tom appeared — silky white rice loosened into broth, topped with minced pork, a soft egg, and ginger cut thin as paper. I meant to eat quickly and move on. Instead I sat on a plastic stool while the morning warmed around me, ordered a second bowl, and watched Chiang Mai shake itself slowly awake. Some breakfasts earn the time they take.

DRAFT C (original preference):
Okay, so here's the thing about Chiang Mai at six in the morning — it smells like woodsmoke and jasmine and something frying in oil, and before you even know what's happening, you're sitting on a plastic stool at a tiny khao tom stall because an older woman gestured at you like she wasn't really giving you a choice. I didn't speak Thai. She didn't speak English. But she handed me this bowl of rice porridge, silky and warm, topped with ginger and scallions, and I just... sat there. An hour, maybe more. Some breakfasts you eat. Others hold you still.

